HEADWORD: Ingulf
<hw>In*gulf"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Ingulfed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Ingulfing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Engulf</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>engulf</asp>.]</altsp>
<def>To swallow up or overwhelm in, or as in, a gulf; to cast into a
gulf. See <er>Engulf</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A river large . . . ⟦br⟧
Passed underneath <qex>ingulfed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ingulfment</ent>⟦br⟧
